<TEXT>
the imminent demolition of hong kongs 
86yearold synagogue to make way for highrise apartments has 
split the jewish community and enraged preservationists 
a group of local jews has sought the help of rabbis in israel 
and britain to save the synagogue and joined lastditch efforts to 
go to court to stop the wreckers ball 
im sorry that it has become such a controversial issue i 
never imagined that it would said robert dorfman chairman of 
the committee that manages the daytoday affairs of ohel leah 
synagogues 230family congregation which includes 23 different 
nationalities 
ohel leah has been the center of jewish life in this british 
colony since 1902 it was built by sir jacob sassoon an iraqi jew 
who came to hong kong from shanghai 
the stately white building with two short towers and an arched 
portico is set in a serene garden on a hillside above hong kongs 
central business district sassoon bequeathed the synagogue and 
surrounding land to the jewish community and set up a trusteeship 
to manage the property 
the plan to redevelop the site comes from the four jewish 
trustees who are led by lord kadoorie an influential tycoon with 
vast utility and hotel holdings the proposal calls for replacing 
the synagogue with a replica and putting up two apartment towers 
about 40stories high that will include a new jewish club 
supporters of the redevelopment plan argue that the old 
synagogue is unsafe and that bigger and better facilities are 
needed for a growing jewish community they maintain that the vast 
majority of the congregation supports the proposal 
opponents dispute the claims that the building is dangerous and 
argue that alternative redevelopment plans are viable under which 
the existing synagogue can remain 
the hong kong government already has overturned a vote by its 
antiquities advisory board to declare the building a proposed 
landmark and has approved a demolition permit for the developers 
but a loosely knit group of dissident congregation members 
banded under the name save our synagogue hope lord immanuel 
jakobovits the chief rabbi of england will issue a ruling that 
could halt the project 
in a letter to the englishlanguage south china morning post 
newspaper the synagogues general committee promised that the 
trustees intend to take his jakobovits advice on religious 
questions connected with the rebuilding of the synagogue 
jakobovits has yet to respond 
three years ago three rabbis from israel signed an opinion that 
quoted ancient commentaries and maimonides a 12th century jewish 
legal scholar in concluding that the synagogues destruction is 
strictly forbidden 
the rabbis ruled the building is one of the worlds city 
synagogues which maimonides said cannot be destroyed because they 
are for the use of all jews and become the property of all jews 
the synagogues trustees contend however that opinion is based 
on erroneous information 
save our synagogue members also are working with nonjewish 
preservationists in trying to save the building through 
bureaucratic and legal channels 
william meachem a member of the antiquities advisory board 
said he is raising 100000 hong kong dollars 12820 for legal 
fees to for action to require the government to put a hold on the 
project 
he described hong kongs overall preservation record as 
atrocious horrible maybe one of the worst in the world 
alan goldstein a member of the synagogues congregation has a 
photograph made of hong kong in the 1920s showing the synagogue as 
the only recognizable building still standing 
much of hong kongs architectural heritage has been replaced by 
commercial skyscrapers and highrise apartments that crowd around 
the territorys famed harbor 
every civilized society in this world today recognizes the 
importance of their cultural heritage and they have certain laws 
and regulations to protect the best examples of their heritage 
said david russell a senior lecturer of architecture at the 
university of hong kong 
our only hope is to try to persuade the government of its 
responsibility said russell although he held out little hope of 
success 
but dorfman insists the issue is for the jews alone 
who are these people who are they to get involved in this 
he said this is our synagogue this is our community 
</TEXT>
