<TEXT>
a private task force is recommending a series 
of actions to provide fit livable and affordable housing for all 
americans by the year 2000 starting with a firstyear 
appropriation of 3 billion 
the report of the national housing task force issued monday 
urges that half the money go to the states as matching funds and 
the remaining 15 million go to cities with no matching 
requirement and few bureaucratic rules on how it is to be spent 
the task force said housing for most poor americans is 
unavailable unaffordable or unfit it said the 3 billion seed 
money should stimulate state and local efforts to develop renovate 
and conserve lowincome housing and to produce 150000 to 200000 
units 
james w rouse a nationally known developer and chairman of the 
26member task force called attention to the growing percentages 
of women and children among the homeless 
this isnt your typical hobo this isnt a person who is a 
drug addict or alchoholic or lazy rouse told a news conference 
these are people who want a place to live and in our country 
think of it theres no place to live i dont think this has ever 
before happened in our country that people like this have nowhere 
to live 
the report recommended that the governments rental assistance 
program be increased by 200000 units instead of the 100000 in the 
1989 federal budget the added cost would be 380 million a year 
it said 
samuel r pierce the secretary of housing and urban 
development issued a statement saying that fresh ideas on low 
income housing always were welcome but the statement went on to 
say that several of the recommendations call for significant 
increases in federal spending and will require require difficult 
budget decisions by the administration and congress 
the national association of realtors praised the report as a 
step in the right direction 
sen alan cranston dcalif chairman of the subcommittee on 
housing and urban affairs said the report is of historic 
importance and copies will be sent to all presidential candidates 
sen alfonse m damato of new york the subcommittees ranking 
republican said a decent place to live is no longer the problem 
of the poor and homeless but the call comes from millions of 
families particularly young families 
the report said that from 1973 to 1983 45 million units half 
occupied by lowincome households were lost to the rental market 
either through demolition or structural conversion 
those who struggle with modest or minimal incomes represent a 
cross section of america said the report they are young 
middle aged elderly disabled they are single parents and intact 
families they are working 
the task force recommended that substantial new capital be 
raised by establishing benevolent loan funds accepting deposits at 
low interest rates from socially motivated investors and 
lending it at belowmarket rates to lowincome housing developers 
and home buyers 
there must be greater emphasis on preserving and improving 
existing lowincome housing and renovation of thousands of units 
the report said and it called for use of taxexempt financing and 
a commitment by the federal government to adequate rental 
assistance it also said the government should allow the federal 
housing administration to offer mortgages to more moderate income 
people 
while the report outlined a 12year program it said 
homelessness is a problem that cant wait and recommended that 
additional funds be made available in 1988 to states and 
communities 
