<TEXT>
the state supreme court threw out a death 
sentence against a vietnam veteran because the sentencing trial 
omitted testimony that the killer of two young girls may have been 
driven by trauma caused by his wartime experiences 
the court ruled unanimously monday that the jury might not have 
sentenced phillip lucero to death if it had been allowed to hear 
the assessment of a veterans counselor 
the ruling ordered a new penaltyphase trial with the previously 
excluded evidence to decide whether lucero should be sentenced to 
death or life without parole 
justice stanley mosk in a separate opinion went further and 
said the court should forbid a death sentence for lucero 
as his patriotic duty he killed our enemies efficiently 
wrote mosk unfortunately after returning home he irrationally 
killed again this time two innocent children there is macabre 
irony in the fact that the society on whose behalf lucero took an 
undetermined number of lives is now seeking to take his life 
in the penalty phase of the trial psychiatrist edward conolley 
testified that lucero suffered posttraumatic stress including 
flashbacks to incidents in which he killed a grenadewielding 
soldier who proved to be an ally and carried rotting corpses from 
the battlefield 
conolley attributed the murders to luceros mental impairment 
compounded by flashbacks that may have been touched off by the 
sound of police helicopters and the cackling of a goose outside his 
home because agitated animals in vietnam often foreshadowed the 
approach of unfriendly forces 
however thensuperior court judge joseph campbell barred 
testimony by thomas wulbrecht a veteran who runs a counseling 
program for vietnam vets at a veterans hospital based on a 
3hour conversation with lucero that did not include the 
circumstances of the murders wulbrecht said he would have 
testified that lucero probably had been driven by the same stress 
syndrome 
justice allen broussard in writing for the court said the jury 
should have been allowed to consider the testimony as an argument 
favoring leniency he said it could have been more persuasive than 
conolleys testimony the prosecution sought to discredit the 
psychiatrist as a hired gun for the defense but could not have 
used the same attack on wulbrecht broussard said 
the court also ruled that campbell wrongly prevented conolley 
from answering questions about whether lucero was likely to repeat 
his crimes or could adjust to prison broussard said 
luceros is the fifth death sentence the court has reversed out 
of 16 it has considered since conservatives gained a majority last 
year all of the reversals have been unanimous 
lucero now 42 was convicted of murdering 7yearold chris 
hubbard and 10yearold teddy engliman his neighbors in the town 
of yucaipa in san bernardino county 
the girls were last seen at the back of luceros lot on an 
afternoon in april 1980 a neighbor heard luceros goose cackling 
and heard lucero tell the girls as they entered his yard that the 
goose would not hurt them after helicopters were called in and a 
fire broke out in luceros house the girls bodies were found in a 
nearby trash container one beaten the other strangled 
the supreme court upheld the murder convictions saying luceros 
approach to the girls and their accompanying him into his yard 
would allow the jury to conclude reasonably that the killings were 
premeditated 
after a turbulent childhood lucero lied about his age joined 
the army at 16 and served three tours of combat in vietnam 
receiving a purple heart and a combat infantry badge 
</TEXT>
