<TEXT>
more than 80 percent of americans favor a 
federal program to provide longterm home care for the chronically 
ill and disabled according to a poll released tuesday 
the survey by louis harris amp associates also found that more 
than 70 percent would support paying for the program by increasing 
medicare payroll taxes for people who make more than 45000 a year 
rep claude pepper dfla released the survey in conjunction 
with a hearing on his fiveyear 25 billion proposal for longterm 
home care house leaders have promised him a floor vote on the bill 
although it has not gone through the usual committee scrutiny 
many members have criticized the plan as too expensive to pass 
this year rep dan rostenkowski dill chairman of the 
taxwriting house ways and means committee has said congress 
cannot enact both peppers plan and another medicare expansion 
shielding the elderly and disabled against catastrophic healthcare 
costs 
catastrophiccost bills already have passed both houses and 
negotiators are working out differences between the two versions 
rep edward roybal dcalif chairman of the house select 
committee on aging and a cosponsor of peppers bill said 
virtually no medicare or insurance coverage is available to 
millions of people with a chronic illness 
we have long believed we were seeing a rising tide of public 
support for a federal longterm care program and the harris poll 
shows us americans are evne more enthusiastic than we imagined 
roybal said in a statement 
the harris survey found that americans of all ages professions 
party affiliations and income levels supported financing a new 
homecare program through an increase in the 145 percent medicare 
payroll tax on upperincome workers 
more than 70 percent of people earning above 50000 supported 
that method of financing although they would bear the brunt of it 
the survey found 
of those questioned 82 percent said they could not afford to 
pay for the costs of providing longterm care either at home or in 
a nursing home including more than 60 percent of those making 
above 50000 a year 
and nearly 80 percent of those polled said they would prefer 
longterm home care to care in a nursing home 
the harris survey questioned 1500 adults across the country in 
telephone interviews feb 1823 the margin of error is plus or 
minus three percentage points 
the survey echoes an earlier poll last fall that found americans 
by an overwhelming majority were willing to pay higher taxes to 
finance longterm care for the elderly 
sixtyeight percent of those questioned in the survey by rl 
associates were willing to shoulder 10 to 60 a month more in 
taxes to pay for the program 
that survey was commissioned by longterm care 88 a coalition 
of senior citizens groups and other organizations hoping to make 
the issue a top priority with presidential candidates 
on a related matter a government report released tuesday said 
the number of elderly americans confined to nursing homes is 
remaining stable even though the raw numbers are rising because of 
an aging population 
there were 13 million nursing home residents at least 65 years 
of age in 1985 up 200000 from 1977 when the last nursing home 
figures were collected 
the report by the department of health and human services said 
the 1985 nursing home population reflected about 1 percent of 
americans 6574 years old being confined to institutions and about 
22 percent of those 85 years and older both percentages were 
essentially unchanged from the 1977 survey 
