a former conrail engineer was sentenced today 
to the maximum term of five years in prison and fined 1000 for 
causing 16 deaths in amtraks worst train accident 
rick l gates 33 of essex pleaded guilty feb 16 to the 
single misdemeanor manslaughter count and admitted in a statement 
of facts to smoking marijuana on the train and failing to make 
several safety checks that might have prevented the accident 
baltimore county circuit court judge joseph p murphy said i 
didnt think he was under the influence of marijuana 
but what he did in terms of failure to follow procedures was 
to show us that he didnt give a damn he just didnt care the 
judge said 
gates and family members in the courtroom wept as prosecutors 
read five victim impact statements from relatives of those killed 
in the crash 
in return for the guilty plea baltimore county states attorney 
sandra oconnor agreed to consolidate the names of all 16 victims 
into one count which reduced the maximum sentence from 80 years 
and 16000 in fines to five years and a 1000 fine 
the plea bargain provoked sharp criticism from families of 
victims and leaders of a new safe travel lobby group safe travel 
america 
i am grossly disappointed that he can cause tens of millions 
of dollars in damage and kill 16 people and still face only five 
years on a misdemeanor charge said dr roger horn whose 
16yearold daughter ceres was killed 
mrs oconnor urged the judge to give gates the maximum penalty 
more than 175 people were injured in the jan 4 1987 crash 
when gates missed a track signal and drove three linked conrail 
locomotives in front of the 660passenger amtrak train traveling 
about 120 mph the impact trapped riders in the wreckage for hours 
in bitter cold weather 
gates was unhurt and his brakeman edward cromwell suffered a 
broken leg 
oconnor said at the time of the plea that the manslaughter 
verdict would send a message that transportation workers cannot 
work under the kind of negligence that mr gates did 
the agreement was announced as jury selection for the gates 
sixweek manslaughter trial was scheduled to begin cromwell who 
had been granted immunity from prosecution was expected to testify 
that he and gates fabricated a story to cover up their drug use on 
the train 
tests performed on blood samples taken from both men after the 
accident showed traces of marijuana and possibly alcohol in their 
systems according to a report by the national transportation 
safety board 
however defense attorneys said no experts could conclude gates 
was impaired from the marijuana lawyers also were expected to cite 
a january ruling by the 9th us circuit court of appeals against 
postcrash drug testing 
mrs oconnor acknowledged that prosecutors had considered the 
court ruling in deciding to accept the plea the ruling has been 
appealed to the supreme court 
