<TEXT>
states seeking to cope with rising prison 
costs may not seize social security benefits received by inmates 
the supreme court ruled tuesday 
the court unanimously struck down an arkansas law that permitted 
authorities to use an inmates social security benefits for state 
purposes 
similar laws have been enacted in michigan ohio oklahoma and 
tennessee the justices had been told 
the arkansas law allowed seizure of veterans administration 
benefits as well although the courts decision did not discuss va 
benefits its rationale appeared to bar seizure of those federal 
payments as well 
the justices in an unsigned opinion said federal law 
unambiguously rules out any attempt to attach social security 
benefits 
noting that the arkansas law allows such attachment the court 
said this amounts to a conflict that the state cannot win 
federal laws creating the social security and veterans 
administration programs bar any legal action aimed at diverting 
benefits from the designated recipients 
the court rejected arguments by arkansas officials that the 
federal laws do not apply to seizures of prison inmates benefits 
because the inmates are being provided with care and 
maintenance 
the impact of tuesdays ruling has been blunted somewhat by laws 
passed by congress in 1980 and 1983 withholding or limiting 
benefits otherwise due imprisoned felons 
the decision also does not affect state laws that require prison 
inmates to reimburse the state from sources other than federal 
benefits for some of the costs of their incarceration 
for example the justices were told that six states require jail 
inmates serving terms for misdemeanors to make such reimbursements 
those states are alabama illinois kentucky missouri nebraska 
and north carolina 
the justices were told that eight states require reimbursement 
by inmates for certain kinds of state claims ranging from medical 
expenses to expenses incurred by quelling riots those states are 
arizona florida maine maryland mississippi nevada north 
dakota and rhode island 
the arkansas legislature in 1981 passed the states inmate care 
and custody reimbursement act under it state authorities may seek 
court approval to seize an inmates estate income from any source 
former inmate george bennett challenged the law he was serving 
11 years of a 21year sentence at a pine bluff prison for 
seconddegree murder when he turned 62 
bennett started receiving 275 a month in social security 
retirement benefits but those payments were confiscated by state 
officials he was released from prison in late 1984 but is seeking 
to recover 3600 in seized benefits 
the arkansas supreme court ruled against him but tuesdays 
ruling reversed the state courts decision 
reagan administration lawyers had opposed the arkansas law 
telling the justices that such legislation would seem to validate 
the attachment of social security and va benefits paid to persons 
confined in state mental hospitals or in other institutions where 
they are provided care by the state 
</TEXT>
