<TEXT>
west virginia university administrators 
set up a committee tuesday to explore the ethical obligations of 
students who do corporate espionage for companies under the 
auspices of the university 
the announcement made by frank franz vice president for 
academic affairs comes one week after the wall street journal 
reported that graduate students in the business school divulged 
sales and inventory figures gained in a study to competitors of the 
businesses they surveyed 
the article points out that the confidentiality of respondents 
was promised but not observed franz said 
the key problem is that the students were put in a very 
unfortunate position by the sponsors of the project and i think 
inappropriate things were asked of them 
franz said the sevenmember committee will consider whether 
students should be required to disclose routinely the sponsor of a 
study its purpose and who will receive the information obtained 
he said the committee also will suggest ways to avoid conflicts 
of interest in internships research projects and other 
opportunities that arise through consulting performed by faculty 
members for private companies 
the journal reported that two groups of students who conducted 
competitive analyses for two caterpillar heavyequipment dealers 
were asked by the dealers to identify the competitors they 
interviewed 
several students said they did one of those involved likened 
the work to spying 
representatives of two of the dealerships interviewed for the 
1987 study said they would not have given out the information if 
they had known the students were working for other dealers 
i feel the way they went about it was very underhanded gary 
clark executive vice president of clark co one of the companies 
in the study told the daily anthenaeum the student newspaper 
now i will probably be on my guard whenever i talk to 
students but i dont blame the students i blame the professor 
terry wilson professor of the marketing 321 class told the 
journal that the students should not have divulged confidential 
information to their clients 
franz said there is no evidence that wilson who is a consultant 
for caterpillar encouraged the students to give the information to 
the dealerships 
