<TEXT>
the proportion of women enrolled in schools 
for health professions has skyrocketed in recent years according 
to a federal statistical analysis issued tuesday 
the most striking increase was in dental schools where women 
made up only 1 percent of enrollment in the 197172 school term by 
the 198586 term the figure was 25 percent 
enrollment of women in medical schools jumped from 11 percent to 
33 percent over the same period and in pharmacy schools from 24 
percent to 56 percent 
those are among figures contained in the 207page health 
united states 1987 a report issued annually by the department of 
health and human services 
most of the figures were released previously as they were being 
compiled by one or more of the dozens of agencies within hhs and 
tend to lag a year or two behind the volumes publication 
the national center for health statistics an arm of the centers 
for disease control organizes the material into an annual report 
as required by law to provide a central storehouse of statistical 
data 
the 1987 volume documents that life expectancy at birth has 
increased dramatically since 1900 for all americans regardless of 
race or sex 
for example a black female born in 1900 could expect to live 
only 335 years compared with 627 years for one born in 1950 and 
735 years for one born in 1985 
although there have been life expectacy gains across the board 
the smallest increase 25 years was among white males a white 
male born in 1900 could expect to live 466 years compared with 
719 years for one born in 1985 
some other highlights 
infant mortality declined only 2 percent between 1984 and 1985 
the smallest drop since 1965 the black infant mortality rate 182 
per 1000 live births is almost twice as high as for white 
infants 93 per 1000 
births to unmarried mothers doubled between 1970 and 1985 from 
11 percent to 22 percent 
between 1970 and 1985 mortality from cancer the second 
leading cause of death increased slightly overall however lung 
cancer deaths among women more than doubled heart disease remains 
the no 1 killer 
