<TEXT>
the government is considering charging space 
shuttle customers up to 245 million a flight for carrying their 
cargo into space a congressional panel was told tuesday 
up to now the national aeronautics and space administration has 
charged 87 million maximum for use of the cargo bay billed to 
users according to how much space they used 
dale myers nasas deputy administrator confirmed that the 245 
million figure was discussed last week by a panel connected to the 
senior interagency group for space a toplevel advisory committee 
for the president 
that is not the final decision myers told sen william 
proxmire dwis at a senate appropriations subcommittee hearing 
on nasas fiscal 1989 budget request he did not dispute proxmires 
contention that nasa lost an 81 vote for the 245 million figure 
in the interagency group 
the total cost of a shuttle flight has varied according to the 
frequency of flights within a given fiscal year a 1985 estimate 
a year before the challenger disaster priced each flight at 150 
million at a rate of 14 launches a year 
nasa has never pressed for full recovery of its costs in the 
first flights of the shuttle beginning in 1981 the cost for 
launching a satellite from the cargo bay was about 10 million 
the agency then instituted a pricing policy of 71 million for a 
full cargo bay meaning that a satellite owner might pay 23 
millionplus if his cargo was launched along with two other 
satellites the charge per cargo bay rose to 87 million per flight 
in october 1985 
myers explained during the hearing and afterward that the 245 
million was sort of an upper limit of all the costs 
its an estimate that includes everything including the 
kitchen sink all the overhead manpower required for checkout all 
the hardware all the fuels all the contingencies that might occur 
due to delays in flights he said 
but asked if that were the amount the space agency would seek to 
recover from cargo bay users myers said no it is not in our 
view a number that would make any sense at all i cant really talk 
too much about it because this is internal planning 
a staff member of the appropriations subcommittee called the 
245 million a nonsubsidized realworld total number for a 
flight on the shuttle if you want to buy it 
the senior interagency group for space includes representatives 
of nasa the cia and the commerce transportation defense and 
state departments 
