former rep paul mccloskey jr said tuesday he 
is considering suing pat robertson to recover 400000 in legal 
fees he incurred when the republican presidential candidate sued 
him for libel 
mccloskey said his lawyers believe they can be prove that 
robertson made frivolous use of the court system in suing mccloskey 
over his statements about robertsons korean war record 
at a national press club luncheon mccloskey repeated the story 
he has told for years about being in marine officer training school 
with robertson and then being shipped to korea in 1950 mccloskey 
contends that while he and others were sent off to combat 
robertson ducked combat duty using the influence of his father the 
late sen a willis robertson dva 
mccloskey said he and others recall robertson boasting about how 
im going to call my daddy to get me out of this thing 
robertson dropped his legal suit against mccloskey earlier this 
month citing a trial opening set for march 8 the date of the 
critical super tuesday series of presidential primaries and 
caucuses in 20 states he said the trial would force him to choose 
between his campaign and the legal case 
however mccloskey contended tuesday that robertson dropped the 
lawsuit because the evidence supporting the former california 
congressmans story was unbeatable 
he said 21 former marines were ready to testify on his side and 
that letters from robertsons father supported his case 
the evidence that robertson brought suit frivolously is in a 
letter written by robertson to a california politician in 1985 in 
which robertson said that mccloskey believed he was telling the 
truth but that his memory was faulty the excongressman said 
that would negate the veracity of a suit claiming mccloskey 
willfully lied about the former television evangelists record 
mccloskey said 
now we have enough to sue him for misusing the legal 
process he said 
robertson however insisted he could have won the case 
every testimony that was to be was already in the record the 
record was closed the record was complete in the record i won 
robertson said at a news conference tuesday in chesapeake va 
unfortunately the judge gave me a hobsons choice that i could 
not abide with 
a federal judge dismissed the case on march 7 after robertston 
agreed to pay court costs but not mccloskeys 400000 in legal 
fees 
