<TEXT>
the senate finance committee agreed tuesday to 
grant a fueltax exemption for farmers and other offtheroad 
diesel users on april 1 and to make corporations foot the bill 
however the future of the proposed relief remained in doubt 
because the house ways and means committee which must originate 
tax bills has scheduled no action on the diesel proposal backers 
of the legislation are holding out hope that the house panel will 
approve a bill this week before adjourning for easter week 
farmers fishermen and others who use diesel for offtheroad 
business purposes traditionally have been exempt from the tax 
which finances highway construction but under a 1987 law aimed at 
preventing cheating they must begin paying the tax on april 1 and 
then apply for a refund when they file their incometax returns 
next year 
the finance committee voted last week to grant these users 
relief from paying the tax at all but because of budget 
restrictions it acted to provide the exemption on oct 1 at the 
direction of the committee sen lloyd bentsen dtexas the 
chairman introduced an amendment tuesday that steps up the relief 
to april 1 
the committee is getting around the budget problem by tightening 
collections of corporate taxes this would cost corporations an 
extra 508 million from 1988 through 1993 with the bulk of the 
additional money coming from expedited collections this year and 
next 
under the change a corporation that shifts its method of 
calculating estimated taxes from one quarter to the next would have 
to make up in the subsequent quarter 96 percent of the reduction 
achieved in the previous period this change would be phased in 
over two years 
providing the dieseltax relief for offroad users will cost 
about 615 million during the same sixyear period another part of 
the package is a taxpayer bill of rights aimed at reducing 
internal revenue service powers in some disputes with taxpayers 
these changes would cost about 517 million through 1993 
other provisions would double the gasguzzler tax on inefficient 
cars mainly expensive imports and limit the abilities of 
distilleries to dodge part of the whisky tax through what is known 
as a wine credit 
the net revenue effect of the package would be to raise taxes by 
104 million over six years 
