been ballyhooed by the official news media 
in the tibetan room of the great hall of the people seat of 
chinas government 19 delegates from tibet gathered for what was 
supposed to be an example of democracy at work 
foreign and chinese reporters crowded the room in anticipation 
of observing delegates engaged in a free exchange of ideas 
but many soon left as one delegate after another to the national 
peoples congress read lengthy prepared speeches praising 
economic reform and chinas opendoor policy and calling for unity 
and perseverence in the great work of socialist construction 
western reporters who attended other provincial discussion 
groups said the action was a little livelier as delegates 
interrupted each other to add remarks or to disagree 
the reporters said they were surprised that their presence 
seemed not to deter delegates from criticizing the implementation 
of policies in their areas 
but most speakers prefaced critical remarks by saying they 
agreed with chinas policies of reform and with the report 
presented by acting premier li peng at fridays opening session of 
the congress 
china has given lavish publicity to what it says is the 
increasingly democratic nature of its government for the first 
time this year there were more candidates than seats in elections 
for local peoples congresses 
the media portrayed the small group discussions as being the 
heart of the democratic exercise the national tv evening news for 
two days has devoted nearly half its domestic news to showing 
delegates in animated exchanges 
but in the tibetan room 20 minutes passed before the first 
delegate spoke out of turn and then it was to support his 
colleagues statements 
at the 2hour meeting delegates were seldom interrupted and no 
one expressed disagreement or a differing viewpoint 
most delegates seemed disinterested smoking absently and 
