<TEXT>
the common markets executive body has 
approved french government aid to giant automaker renault but has 
set certain conditions on the assistance 
the european economic community commission said tuesday it has 
approved french aid to renault of 20 billion french francs or 
about 354 billion at current exchange rates 
the decision made a month before the french presidential 
elections marked the end of a twoyear investigation into 
government assistance to regie nationale des usines renault which 
is a state agency 
the decision means that the french government is authorized to 
proceed with a 12 billion franc writeoff of renaults debt 
renault had 464 billion francs of debt at the end of 1987 
the commission said in a statement it also approved a 
previouslymade capital injection into renault of 8 billion francs 
because it had not been used to undercut prices in the 12nation 
common market 
the commission has the power to investigate government aid to 
industry because of the potential anticompetitive effects of such 
assistance 
however the commission said it approved the aid under certain 
conditions including the conversion this year of renault into a 
stateowned company from a state agency which escapes company law 
other conditions included the completion of an 834 billion 
franc restructuring program and a pledge from the french government 
not to grant further aid 
the french industry ministry said in a statement in paris that 
the commissions decision was good for the company it said 
renault would now be in a position to compete on an equal footing 
with its main competitors 
the commission said renault had been particularly hard hit 
by the crisis in the common markets auto sector in the early 1980s 
when many companies had to reorganize their activities in the face 
of reduced demand and rising imports from japan 
renaults restructuring plan which runs through 1990 involves 
modernizing factories cutting the workforce by at least 38000 and 
reducing production capacity by more than 25 percent 
the commission said the program would make a significant 
contribution to resolving some of the problems of the european 
car industry 
</TEXT>
