<DOCNO> AP880329-0258 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the 12nation european economic 
community loses at least 250 billion a year in extra costs and 
lost economic opportunities by staying divided along national 
borders a twoyear study concludes 
the study which was released tuesday is designed to give 
economic undepinning to the trade blocs plan to abolish national 
frontiers and create a single european market by the end of 1992 
the report concluded that fusing the economies of the individual 
member states into one would add 5 percent to the blocs gross 
domestic product and create up to 5 million new jobs 
the report was prepared by a team of economists supervised by 
paolo cecchini a former senior eec official 
jacques delors president of the eec executive commission said 
at a press conference that he hoped the report would launch a 
european debate about economic integration we are simply 
providing food for thought we want to get a debate going he 
said 
he said the purpose of the study was not to provide an economic 
forecast but rather to outline the economic potential of a europe 
united in a single market 
lord arthur cockfield the eec commissioner responsible for the 
integration process gave a more prosaic appraisal of the study 
we wanted to show there is a lot more juice to be squeezed from 
this particular lemon 
pointing to the more than 6000 pages that the report and its 
underlying studies contain cockfield said nothing like it has 
ever been done before 
he said the results show clearly the extent to which the 
division of europe results in noncompetitive behavior missed 
opportunities high unemployment and higher prices 
according to the study the eec stands to gain from market 
integration the equivalent of at least 250 billion a year largely 
by foregoing the cost of border controls and by improving 
productivity and competitiveness 
abolishing controls and removing nontariff barriers to trade 
the report concluded could save up to 992 billion and shave as 
much as 35 percent of the cost of products 
an additional 756 billion could be gained from exploiting 
economies of scale more fully the report estimated 
restoring competition in statecontrolled industries and 
reducing business ineffectiveness would add 57 billion in 
economic benefits the report said 
the study predicted that in addition to boosting output 
employment and the standard of living the creation of a single 
market would simultaneously cool the economy deflating consumer 
prices by an average of 6 percent 
deregulation of public transport the energy industry banking 
indurance and defence procurement would lead to price cuts of up to 
20 percent the report said 
the report estimated that market integration alone would add 45 
percent to the gross domestic product and add 2 million new jobs 
but if combined with tax reduction and increased spending the 
report said a single market would boost gross domestic product by 
7 percent and create 5 million new jobs 
the report did not estimate which eec countries would benefit 
most from the single market but said all 12 were likely to make 
substantial economic gains 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

