<TEXT>
new home sales which had fallen for three 
months following the october collapse of the stock market soared 
203 percent in february the fastest increase in almost two years 
the government said tuesday 
the commerce department said that new singlefamily homes were 
sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 628000 units it was 
the first monthly increase since a 14 percent rise in october but 
it still left sales 149 percent below where they were a year ago 
sales had fallen 103 percent in january 68 percent in 
december and 42 percent in november declines which analysts had 
blamed on high mortgage rates and consumer jitters following the 
record plunge in stock prices that occurred on oct 19 
because housing is often the first sector to weaken at the start 
of a new recession the string of declines had raised concerns 
about whether another downturn was imminent 
but analysts said the strong february rebound erased those 
worries and indicated housing should strengthen further in coming 
months 
the february numbers spell relief and optimism said david 
seiders chief economist for the national association of home 
builders we feel we are back on track where we should be 
james christian chief economist of the us league of savings 
institutions said the february housing performance is another 
piece of evidence that we are shrugging off the aftershocks from 
the stock market crash 
christian predicted that new home sales would rise further 
during the spring sales season and help boost sales for the entire 
year to around 650000 while that would be down from the 671000 
new homes sold in 1987 it would still be considered a strong sales 
year for the industry 
analysts said it is unlikely that mortgage rates will fall much 
further fixedrate mortgages currently stand at 999 percent down 
from a high last year of 1158 percent just before the stock market 
decline 
economists predicted rates would begin rising later this spring 
and would probably top 11 percent by the end of the year 
the economy is too strong and the dollar is too weak to 
believe that interest rates will go down from here said martin 
regalia chief economist of the national council of savings 
institutions 
the big february sales rebound was the largest monthly increase 
since a 21 percent gain in march 1986 it was accompanied by a 
